  <exercise>
    <title>Identify distributions, Part I</title><!--  #21 -->
    <statement>
      <p>
        Four plots are presented below.
        The plot at the top is a distribution for a population.
        The mean is 10 and the standard deviation is 3.
        Also shown below is a distribution of (1) a single random sample of 100 values from this population, (2) a distribution of 100 sample means from random samples with size 5, and (3) a distribution of 100 sample means from random samples with size 25.
        Determine which plot (A, B, or C) is which and explain your reasoning.
      </p>
      <image width="50%" source="images/distributions/cltSimSYM_pop.png" />
      <sidebyside>
       	<image width="32%" source="images/distributions/cltSimSYM_n5.png" />
       	<image width="32%" source="images/distributions/cltSimSYM_samp.png" />
       	<image width="32%" source="images/distributions/cltSimSYM_n25.png" />
      </sidebyside>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        The centers are the same in each plot, and each data set is from a nearly normal distribution, though the histograms may not look very normal since each represents only 100 data points. The only way to tell which plot corresponds to which scenario is to examine the variability of each distribution. Plot B is the most variable, followed by Plot A, then Plot C. This means Plot B will correspond to the original data, Plot A to the sample means with size 5, and Plot C to the sample means with size 25.
      </p>
    </solution>
